Abstract = {{High-energy radiation can be generated by colliding a relativistic
   electron bunch with a high-intensity laser pulse-a process known as
   Thomson scattering. In the nonlinear regime the emitted radiation
   contains harmonics. For a laser pulse whose length is comparable to its
   wavelength, the carrier envelope phase changes the behavior of the
   motion of the electron and therefore the radiation spectrum. Here we
   show theoretically and numerically the dependency of the spectrum on the
   intensity of the laser and the carrier envelope phase. Additionally, we
   also discuss what experimental parameters are required to measure the
   effects for a beamed pulse.}},
